headline.main: NEW-YORK CITY.; EPISCOPAL CONVENTION. Seventieth Convention of the Diocese of New-York, THE PROVISIONAL BISHOP. Adjournment of the Convention. THIRD DAY. HOMICIDE. Inquest on the Body of Frederick C. Schlaefer. Meeting of Dry Goods Clerks. Aid to Vicksburg. FIRES. COLD WEATHER.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Convention reassembled at 9 o'clock yesterday. There were but few present in the body of the Church or in the galleries, during morniug prayer, which was read by Rev. T. BABCOCK, of Cohoes, assisted in the lessons by Rev. Mr. CALDY, of West Troy. After morning prayer, several of the clerical and lay delegates arrived.

headline.main: PHILADELPHIA.; The Weather and the Yellow Fover--Immense Meeting-Fatal Accident-Shocking Affair-Police Matters--The markets, &c.

docs.lead_paragraph: The weather, to-day, has been cool, yet pleasant. Our city continues thronged with strangers, most of whom are from the South and Southwest. With now and then a case of yellow fever, in the "infected district," the health of Philadelphia is improving, and I doubt not but the bill of mortality, for the present week, will show a decided decrease.

headline.main: NEW-YORK CITY.; CRIIES AND CASUALTIES. Mysterious Murder in the Eighth Ward. Supposed Murder by Poison--Verdict of Pericarditis. Casnalties. SUPERIOR COURT.

docs.lead_paragraph: About 10 o'clock or Thursday night, two men, named JACOB WILSON and AUSTIN RANEIN, found a young man, apparently a German immigrant, lying on the sidewalk in West-stret, near Hammersley. He was perfectly insensible, evidently from loss of blood resulting from a terrible gash in the throat, and a fracture of the shull.
